## Development Commands

**[INSTRUCTIONS]**: Document the main development workflows in your project. Replace examples with your actual justfile recipes.

Use `./just` to run common development commands. Run `./just` to see all available commands.

```bash
# Workflows (use these after developing functionality)
./just fix          # Auto-fix lint + format code
./just validate     # Quick check: lint + typecheck (no tests)
./just check        # Full check: lint + typecheck + tests
./just dev          # Full cycle: fix code, then run all checks

# Individual commands
./just sync         # Install dependencies
./just test         # Run all tests (quiet: -q --tb=short)
./just testv        # Run tests verbose
./just test-file <path>   # Run specific test file
./just test-fast    # Run fast tests only (excludes @pytest.mark.slow)
./just test-slow    # Run slow tests only
./just test-parallel      # Run all tests in parallel
./just test-fast-parallel # Run fast tests in parallel
./just lint         # Lint code (quiet: only errors shown)
./just typecheck    # Type check (compact output)
./just fmt          # Format code (quiet)
./just notebook     # Launch Jupyter
./just clean        # Clean cache files
```

### Output Filtering (Token Savings)

All dev commands use quiet/compact output modes to save tokens:
- **pytest**: `-q --tb=short` configured in `pyproject.toml` (~70% reduction)
- **ruff**: `-q` flag in justfile (~60% reduction)
- **mypy**: `pretty = false` in `pyproject.toml` (~50% reduction)
- **pre-commit**: `-q` flag in justfile (~50% reduction)

To get verbose output when debugging, use `./just testv` or run tools directly with `-v`.

